title: T4 Manual
summary: Manual for the Schilling Robotics TITAN 4 manipulator system - a position-controlled, 7-function manipulator rated for 4 km or 7 km depth. The TITAN 4 is widely regarded as the industry's premier manipulator; it offers accurate position control, a compact design and a high lift-to-weight ratio, using titanium construction for durability.
notes: The manual describes the T4's large operating envelope (1.92 m reach) and its ability to deliver up to 122 kg payload at full extension. Features include an advanced master controller for precise motion, interchangeable jaws, wrist-mounted camera and slip rings, plus joint-by-joint or master/slave control modes. The manipulator has been industry standard for over 35 years and is offered with 4 km or 7 km depth-rated versions. Use the manual for installation, operation and maintenance.

title: Atlas Manual
summary: Manual for the Schilling Robotics ATLAS manipulator - a seven-function, rate-controlled heavy-lift grabber arm rated for 6.5 km depth. The ATLAS arm is designed for heavy load handling with a high lift-to-weight ratio and durable aluminum construction.
notes: The ATLAS provides a large operating envelope and dexterous grabber for grasping and lifting heavy objects or anchoring the ROV to structures. With seven functions and a long service life, it is field-proven for tasks that require reliable heavy-lift capability. The manual outlines operation, maintenance, and system integration for subsea use at depths up to 6.5 km.

title: Constructor 5 and 6 ROV Specifications and Interface Manual
file_name: Constructor 5 and 6 ROV Specifications and Interface Manual
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/ROV-AST-MAN-004 Constructor 5 and 6 ROV Specifications and Interface Manual.pdf
summary: Provides specifications and interface details for DeepOcean's Constructor 5 and 6 work-class ROVs. The manual sets out the ROV's dimensions, power, payload, thruster configuration, electronics interfaces and hydraulic capabilities to ensure that equipment connected to the vehicle complies with the system requirements.
notes: Typical Constructor-class ROVs use multiple hydraulic thrusters, provide high bollard pull in forward, lateral and vertical directions, support numerous hydraulic functions and sensors, and accommodate standard connector and power interfaces. Use this document to match tooling and control equipment to the vehicle's interface and to plan deck integration.

pdf_url: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/ROV-AST-MAN-004 Constructor 5 and 6 ROV Specifications and Interface Manual.pdf

title: Volume 01 Constructor 05 System General
summary: General system manual for the Kystdesign Constructor 5 ROV. It outlines the vehicle's overall design, including mechanical layout, control system architecture, and user interface. The manual describes the ergonomic pilot interface, sensor connectors (up to 35 electrical connectors) and the vehicle's performance capabilities such as bollard pull and payload.
notes: The document explains the ROV's basic characteristics (power 160 kW, depth rating 3000 msw, through-frame lift 3000 kg, payload 400 kg) and lists auto functions (AutoPOS, AutoTRACK) and remote operation capability. It also covers the pilot station, PDU, container options and sensor/lighting interfaces.

title: Volume 02 Constructor 05 Hydraulic System
summary: Details the hydraulic system of the Constructor 5 ROV. It describes the main and auxiliary hydraulic circuits, valve packs, compensators and thruster interfaces. The system uses multiple valve packs controlling up to 24 bi-directional functions, with flows ranging from 10 L min to 150 L min and pilot-operated high-flow manifolds for the main (300 L min) and auxiliary systems.
notes: The manual outlines the hydraulic power unit, reservoir, filters and pumps, as well as the design of the main (260 bar) and auxiliary (300 L min) circuits. It explains the use of compensators for positive system pressure and provides schematics for valve packs, thruster feed lines and return manifolds.

title: 16 litre Compensator
summary: Hydraulic compensator with 16 L volume. A spring acting on a rolling diaphragm maintains the hydraulic circuit at a small over-pressure relative to ambient seawater to prevent seawater ingress. Features include a low-hysteresis rolling diaphragm, optional analogue volume sensor, and visual oil level indicator.
notes: Specifications: capacity 15.8 L; pressure range 0.15-0.25 bar above ambient; four BSPP connections; length 472 mm (588 mm at full stroke); weight ~24 kg; depth rating 3000 m with 6000 m option; mechanical interface via clamps. Suitable for ROV hydraulic systems to maintain positive pressure.

title: 1,2litre Compensator
summary: Compact hydraulic compensator (1.2 L volume). Like the 16-L version, it uses a spring and rolling diaphragm to maintain the hydraulic circuit slightly above ambient pressure, reducing risk of seawater ingress. An optional analogue volume sensor allows remote monitoring.
notes: Specifications: capacity 1.28 L (or 1.22 L depending on configuration); pressure range 0.15-0.55 bar; five BSPP ports; length 385 mm; weight 3.27-4.33 kg; depth rating 3000 m with 6000 m option; mechanical interface via clamps. Designed for ROVs and subsea hydraulics.

title: MAIN Hyd
summary: General arrangement and parts list for the main hydraulic circuit of the Constructor ROV. It identifies the major components (pump, reservoir, filters, compensator, and valve packs), flow paths and pressure settings required to supply high-pressure fluid for thrusters and tooling.
notes: The main hydraulic system provides high flow (up to ~300 L min) at working pressures around 260 bar. It includes pressure and return manifolds, pressure relief valves and gauge points to allow monitoring and maintenance. Use this document to trace lines and confirm hose connections when servicing.

title: Hyd hoses
summary: Inventory and routing guide for the ROV's hydraulic hoses. It lists hose sizes, pressure ratings, part numbers and end connections for each circuit, ensuring correct hose selection and installation.
notes: Proper hose routing avoids tight bends and chafe. Hoses must be rated for the system's operating pressure and have corrosion-resistant fittings. Periodic inspection for wear and leaks is critical for safe operation.

title: Hyd system GA
summary: General arrangement drawing of the complete hydraulic system. It shows the physical layout of hydraulic components (pumps, manifolds, valve packs, compensators, thrusters) and the routing of pressure, return and case-drain lines.
notes: Use the GA to understand the spatial arrangement when assembling or troubleshooting. The drawing complements the detailed schematics by illustrating component locations and mounting interfaces.

title: TCU GA
summary: General arrangement for the Thruster Control Unit. It depicts the assembly of proportional valves, pilot lines and sensors that control the ROV's thrusters.
notes: Understanding the TCU layout is important for maintenance: the GA identifies port labels, solenoid connections and hydraulic line routing. Follow manufacturer torque and cleanliness requirements when removing or installing valves.

title: ACU GA
summary: General arrangement for the Auxiliary Control Unit. This drawing shows the arrangement of hydraulic valves and manifolds used to operate manipulators and auxiliary tooling.
notes: The ACU GA is essential for identifying valve pack positions, servo valves and pilot connections. Use it alongside schematics to ensure proper assembly and to locate relief and check valves in the auxiliary circuit.

title: GFVP GA
summary: General arrangement drawing for the General-Flow Valve Pack (GFVP). It outlines the physical layout of the multi-function valve pack that distributes hydraulic power to smaller tools and actuators.
notes: The GA lists valve positions, connection ports and mounting holes. Reference this when installing or replacing valves to maintain proper port orientation and to ensure O-rings and seals are correctly fitted.

title: AUX Hyd
summary: Detailed description of the auxiliary hydraulic system. It explains the design of the high-flow auxiliary circuit, including its own pump, reservoir, filters and valve pack, which provide large flows for tools such as dredgers or torque tools.
notes: The auxiliary system offers up to 300 L min flow at high pressure, independent of the main circuit. It is equipped with a separate compensator to maintain positive pressure and uses dedicated relief and check valves. The manual includes schematics, maintenance instructions and troubleshooting tips.

title: Poppet logic element
file_name: Constructor hyd pos 22 Poppet logic element
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 22 Poppet logic element.pdf
summary: Vent-to-open, spring-biased closed logic element used as a poppet-style directional control in hydraulic circuits. When pilot pressure is applied to the control port, the poppet opens to allow flow; in absence of pilot pressure the valve blocks flow.
notes: Logic elements are often installed in cavities within valve blocks to create custom pressure or flow-control functions. They must be used with clean hydraulic fluid and installed with the correct cavity tools and seals to prevent leakage. Typical pressure ratings exceed 300 bar.

title: Relief Valve 3/8BSPP 0,8 Bar
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 18 Relief Valve 0,8Bar.pdf
summary: Low-pressure relief valve with BSPP threads factory set at ~0.8 bar. It opens at the preset pressure to protect compensators and reservoirs from over-pressure, venting excess fluid back to tank.
notes: Install this valve in the return or case-drain line of the compensator or reservoir. Ensure it is oriented correctly and free of contamination; mis-adjustment may affect system pressure. Check the set pressure periodically with a calibrated gauge.

title: Check Valve
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 17 Check Valve.pdf
summary: Direct-operated check valve (Parker C5V series) that allows free flow in one direction and blocks reverse flow. A spring holds the ball on its seat until the cracking pressure is reached, after which flow occurs from port A to port B; reverse flow is blocked.
notes: The C5V series mounts on SAE flanges and is offered in multiple sizes with spring options and high maximum working pressures up to 420 bar. Correct orientation is essential: install so that flow is allowed in the desired direction and ensure the seat is clean and undamaged. Reverse flow is prevented to protect pumps and prevent back-pressure.
local_path_raw: rov-ref-app-v2\public\assets\pdfs\Manuals\Constructor 5\Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic\Attachments\Constructor hyd pos 17 Check Valve.pdf
pdf_url: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 17 Check Valve.pdf

title: Pressure Sensor 20 Bar
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 16 Pressure Sensor.pdf
summary: Low-range pressure transmitter (e.g., Danfoss MBS 1200 series) for measuring pressures up to 20 bar in mobile hydraulic systems. The fully welded design offers high burst and over-pressure capability, robust resistance to vibration and shock, excellent EMC protection, and long-term stability.
notes: Available with 4-20 mA or voltage outputs and a variety of pressure and electrical connections. Stainless steel wetted parts ensure compatibility with most hydraulic fluids. Use for monitoring reservoir or case-drain pressure; calibrate periodically for accuracy.

notes: Provides reliable measurement of main or auxiliary system pressure with minimal drift. Choose appropriate pressure range and output signal for the control system. Protect the sensor from pressure spikes and install with proper sealing.

part_no: WDPF A03 ADB V 5 G24 M35/55
file_name: Constructor hyd pos 14 NG3 Proportional directional valve NO
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 14 NG3 Proportional directional valve NO.pdf
summary: Direct-operated proportional spool valve (NG3-Mini size) that is normally open. A proportional solenoid controls spool position to meter flow through the valve, providing precise control with low hysteresis.
notes: Features include high resolution, large flow capacity (Q_max 10 L min) and working pressure up to 350 bar. Used in mobile and industrial hydraulics for accurate speed control of actuators. Maintain fluid cleanliness to avoid spool sticking; calibrate solenoid current for desired flow.

local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 13 NG3 Non Return Valve.pdf
summary: Pilot-operated check (non-return) valve for NG3 mini size. It allows free flow in one direction and blocks reverse flow until pilot pressure is applied. Maximum working pressure ~32 MPa, cracking pressure 0.2 MPa and flow up to 8 L min.
notes: The valve mounts as a sandwich plate and weighs approximately 0.56 kg. Use to hold actuators in position and prevent backflow; pilot pressure from the downstream port releases the check for controlled reverse flow. Install with correct orientation and check for leakage.

title: Proportional directional valve - normally open
file_name: Constructor hyd pos 12 Proportional directional valve NO
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 12 Proportional directional valve NO.pdf
summary: Hydraulic proportional, pilot-operated directional valve (e.g., HydraForce PE16-S67H) that is normally open. Remote pilot pressure at port 1 or 6 shifts the spring-centred spool proportionally, controlling flow from port 3 to port 4; the symmetrical spool provides meter-in and meter-out control.
notes: Features include hardened spool and cage for long life, good linearity and excellent metering characteristics. Rated up to 345 bar and flows around 90 L min. Use for bi-directional control of motors or cylinders; maintain proper pilot pressure and fluid cleanliness.
local_path_raw: rov-ref-app-v2\public\assets\pdfs\Manuals\Constructor 5\Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic\Attachments\Constructor hyd pos 12 Proportional directional valve NO.pdf

file_name: Constructor hyd pos 11 Proportional directional valve NC
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 11 Proportional directional valve NC.pdf
summary: Hydraulic proportional directional valve (cartridge-style) that is spring-centred and normally closed. Applying pilot pressure moves the spool to open flow paths, providing proportional control over direction and speed.
notes: Like the normally open version, this valve uses a hardened spool and cage for durability and offers good metering characteristics and linearity. Typical maximum pressure is ~345 bar and flow around 90 L min. Use in circuits where flow should be blocked until commanded; ensure pilot signal is stable.

file_name: Constructor hyd pos 10 Proportional reducing - relieving valve
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 10 Proportional reducing - relieving valve.pdf
summary: Pilot-operated proportional pressure reducing/relieving valve (HydraForce TS12-36). The regulated pressure at port 2 is proportional to the solenoid current; excess pressure is relieved to tank, maintaining a controlled downstream pressure for hydraulic actuators.
notes: Rated for port-1/port-2 pressures up to 275.8 bar; available with 12 or 24 V coils and standard waterproof options. Use to control auxiliary circuits requiring variable pressure; proper filtration and coil voltage are important.
local_path_raw: rov-ref-app-v2\public\assets\pdfs\Manuals\Constructor 5\Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic\Attachments\Constructor hyd pos 10 Proportional reducing - relieving valve.pdf

title: Proportional reducing / relieving valve
file_name: Constructor hyd pos 09 Proportional reducing - relieving valve
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 09 Proportional reducing - relieving valve.pdf
summary: Direct-acting proportional pressure reducing/relieving valve (HydraForce EHPR08-33). With the coil de-energised, flow is free from port 1 to port 3. Energising the coil connects port 2 to port 1 and increases the reduced pressure; if pressure at port 1 exceeds the set value it is relieved to port 3.
notes: Features 12 or 24 V coils with optional manual override and waterproof designs. Suitable for mineral-based or synthetic fluids. Provides proportional pressure control in smaller circuits; limit flow and protect from contamination to ensure smooth operation.
local_path_raw: rov-ref-app-v2\public\assets\pdfs\Manuals\Constructor 5\Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic\Attachments\Constructor hyd pos 09 Proportional reducing - relieving valve.pdf

title: Proportional Pressure Relief Valve
file_name: Constructor hyd pos 08 Proportional pressure reducing valves
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 08 Proportional pressure reducing valves.pdf
summary: Direct-operated proportional pressure relief valve in screw-in cartridge form (e.g., Wandfluh BDPPM18 or B_P_A03). The solenoid current sets the relief pressure; when reached, the valve opens to connect the protected line to tank, maintaining system pressure within a desired range.
notes: The valve offers good flow capacity using a differential-area design; typical Q_max 8 L min and p_max 350 bar (nominal pressure range to 315 bar). Use in hydraulic circuits to protect against overload while allowing remote electrical control of pressure. Back pressure at the tank port influences the set pressure, so plumbing must minimize back-pressure.

summary: Standard mechanical pressure relief valve for medium-pressure hydraulic systems. It is adjustable and opens when system pressure exceeds the set value, protecting components from over-pressure.
notes: Typically installed near the pump outlet or in branch circuits. Adjust the set pressure according to system requirements; ensure fluid cleanliness to prevent seat damage. Routine testing ensures reliable protection.

notes: Rated for Q_max 20 L min and p_max 350 bar; nominal reduced pressure up to 200 bar. Used where variable downstream pressure is required. When de-energised, flow is unrestricted from A to T; maintain oil cleanliness and calibrate current for desired pressure.

title: Water absorbing filter element
local_path: ../assets/pdfs/Manuals/Constructor 5/Constructor 05 - Volume 2 Hydraulic/Attachments/Constructor hyd pos 05 Cardev Filter.pdf
summary: Filter element containing super-absorbent polymer designed to remove free and emulsified water from hydraulic fluid. As water is absorbed, the polymer swells and reduces flow, prompting replacement. Typical elements remove water down to 100 ppm.
notes: Use these elements in return lines or offline filtration to prevent corrosion and component wear. Replace when differential pressure exceeds manufacturer's recommendation or when the element has absorbed its maximum water content. Not reusable; dispose of saturated elements properly.

notes: The unit includes a visual or electronic clogging indicator. Install in a location with easy access for maintenance. Replace the internal element when saturated or when differential pressure indicates significant blockage.

title: Thruster
summary: Hydraulic thruster (Sub-Atlantic SA380/SA300 series). These thrusters have rugged lightweight construction and ceramic shaft seals to ensure reliability in deep-water operations. They produce near-equal forward and reverse thrust and can be quickly serviced due to a cartridge-style seal assembly.
notes: Available in several propeller sizes (SA300, SA380, SA420, SA500) and various motor displacements to match hydraulic parameters. Thrusters offer efficient performance and are often used on work-class ROVs. Maintain seals and monitor hydraulic flow to maximise thrust output.

title: Thruster
summary: Second thruster entry representing another Sub-Atlantic thruster configuration. Like other Sub-Atlantic thrusters, it features durable construction, near-equal forward/reverse thrust and compatibility with multiple motor displacements.
notes: Designed for integration on work-class ROVs, with quick-change seal cartridges and the ability to retrofit older ROVs. Specific performance parameters depend on propeller size and motor selection. Regular inspection of seals and propeller is necessary.

title: Light Box GA

notes: Use for component location/orientation and connector placement. Confirm revision and any build-specific notes.

title: Constructor 5 24VDC for Atlas Arm
summary: 24 VDC supply reference for the Atlas manipulator arm integration on the ROV.
notes: Use to confirm supply source, protection and routing. Check voltage at load under command, not just open-circuit.

title: Breaker
summary: Resettable circuit breaker used to protect electrical circuits from over‑current faults.
notes: Check trip rating and wiring terminations. If it trips repeatedly, isolate and fault-find before resetting.

title: Filter/Auto ranging Rectifier Module ( FARM )
summary: Vicor FARM (Filter/Auto‑Ranging Rectifier Module) used to convert a wide AC input to a regulated DC bus for downstream DC‑DC converters.
notes: Verify input range and DC bus output before suspecting downstream converters. Check cooling/airflow and connectors in the pod.

title: DC-DC converter module 300Vin / 12Vout / 150Watts
summary: High‑voltage DC‑DC converter module that steps the system HV bus down to a local low‑voltage rail (e.g., 12V/24V/48V) for control electronics and auxiliaries.
notes: Confirm HV input (150V or 300V) and expected output rail before swapping. Inspect for overheating, loose pins, and water ingress signs.

title: DC-DC converter module 300Vin / 48Vout / 150Watts
summary: High‑voltage DC‑DC converter module that steps the system HV bus down to a local low‑voltage rail (e.g., 12V/24V/48V) for control electronics and auxiliaries.
notes: Confirm HV input (150V or 300V) and expected output rail before swapping. Inspect for overheating, loose pins, and water ingress signs.

title: DC-DC converter module 300Vin / 24Vout / 250Watts
summary: High‑voltage DC‑DC converter module that steps the system HV bus down to a local low‑voltage rail (e.g., 12V/24V/48V) for control electronics and auxiliaries.
notes: Confirm HV input (300V) and expected output rail before swapping. Inspect for overheating, loose pins, and water ingress signs.

title: DC-DC converter module 150Vin / 24Vout / 250Watts
summary: High‑voltage DC‑DC converter module that steps the system HV bus down to a local low‑voltage rail (e.g., 12V/24V/48V) for control electronics and auxiliaries.
notes: Confirm HV input (150V) and expected output rail before swapping. Inspect for overheating, loose pins, and water ingress signs.

title: Light Control Boards
summary: Controller electronics/driver boards for the ROV lighting system, typically handling dimming, switching, and protection for light outputs.
notes: If lights fail, check power feed, fuses/breakers, and output connectors at the light box. Swap board only after confirming correct supply voltage.

title: Link Family
summary: Optical communications link hardware used to transport video/data between subsea (control pod) and surface equipment.
notes: Confirm correct fibre routing and mating connectors. Check SFP/CWDM compatibility (wavelength/channel) when troubleshooting comms.

title: Analogue Video Board (AV Card)
summary: Analogue video interface board used to condition/route composite video signals within the system.
notes: Check input signal present at camera, then follow through mux/cards. Poor video can be caused by grounding/shield issues or connector corrosion.

title: Digital Video Board (DV Card)
summary: Analogue video interface board used to condition/route composite video signals within the system.
notes: Check input signal present at camera, then follow through mux/cards. Poor video can be caused by grounding/shield issues or connector corrosion.

title: Ethernet Board (Optional)
summary: Ethernet interface board (optional) providing additional network connectivity or ports for the system.
notes: Only fitted on some builds. Verify network configuration (IP/VLAN) and physical link indicators before replacing hardware.

title: PECL Board (Optional)
summary: PECL (high‑speed differential logic) interface board (optional) used for high‑speed signalling/transport in the comms stack.
notes: Treat as part of the high‑speed link chain—check terminations, connectors and any paired mux modules. Only fitted on some builds.

title: SFP MR80D-Cxx
summary: SFP optical transceiver module used to convert electrical Ethernet/serial data to fibre (and back) for subsea/surface comms.
notes: Match wavelength/optic type to the system design. Clean fibre end-faces and confirm link LEDs/diagnostics before replacement.

title: CWDM C-80-D-B-S-S-13-1-T55
summary: CWDM (Coarse Wavelength Division Multiplexing) optical module used to combine/separate multiple wavelengths on a single fibre.
notes: Ensure channel plan matches the installed SFPs/optics. Watch for connector type and fibre polarity when troubleshooting.

title: Gb Ethernet Switch (Optional)
summary: Gigabit Ethernet switch (optional) used to distribute network connections inside the pod/surface rack.
notes: Confirm power supply and link status per port. Optional item—may not be present on all systems. Keep a known-good spare if used offshore.

title: Relay Card
summary: Relay interface card used to switch power or control signals to loads (e.g., lights, valves, auxiliaries).
notes: Check coil drive and contact outputs. Relays can fail intermittently—inspect for heat damage and verify correct load current.

title: GFD Card
summary: Ground Fault Detection (GFD) card used to monitor insulation/earth leakage and provide protection/alarm functions.
notes: If nuisance trips occur, inspect cabling/penetrators for insulation breakdown and moisture. Verify calibration/settings per system docs.

title: Master Card
summary: Main control/master electronics card that coordinates I/O and system communications in the control pod.
notes: Treat as critical spares item. Before swapping, confirm stable power rails and check for obvious connector/edge damage.

title: Video Card
summary: System video distribution/processing card used to route camera feeds through the control pod electronics stack.
notes: Trace signal path (camera → mux/cards → topside) before replacing. Many ‘video faults’ are connectors or shielding rather than the card.

title: Serial card
summary: Serial communications interface card used for RS‑232/RS‑485 style links between subsea and surface equipment.
notes: Confirm baud rate/protocol and pinout. Check for correct grounding and avoid hot-plugging where possible.

title: Video Mux
summary: Video multiplexer module used to combine/switch multiple video signals for transport over limited channels.
notes: If multiple cameras affected, suspect mux or shared power. Check channel selection/control signals and connector condition.

title: Ethernet Mux (Optional)
summary: Ethernet multiplexer module (optional) used to aggregate or transport Ethernet channels through the comms system.
notes: Only fitted on some builds. Confirm link integrity end-to-end (switch/SFP/CWDM) and check for correct configuration.

title: PECL Mux (Optional)
summary: PECL multiplexer module (optional) used with high‑speed differential signalling paths in the comms stack.
notes: Verify paired PECL boards and cabling/terminations. High‑speed links are sensitive to poor connections and water ingress.

title: Pressure Relief Valve
summary: Pressure relief/vent valve fitted to protect enclosures or hydraulic circuits by relieving over‑pressure in the control pod.
notes: Do not adjust unless instructed by OEM. If leaking/venting, check for blocked breathers, incorrect compensation, or over‑pressure events.

title: Driver Card
summary: Driver electronics card in the valve pack, typically providing coil drive to hydraulic solenoids/actuators.
notes: Check coil resistances and supply voltage before swapping. Look for heat damage and water ingress in valve pack connectors.

title: Umbilical
summary: Main umbilical cable on the winch—carries power, fibre/communications and auxiliaries between vessel and ROV system.
notes: Handle bends carefully (respect minimum bend radius). Record terminations and continuity/insulation test results after repairs.

title: Tether
summary: Tether cable between TMS and the ROV—typically carries power, comms and hydraulics (depending on build).
notes: Common fault points are terminations/penetrators and crush damage. Keep a termination checklist and do insulation tests after work.

title: Electrical Motor
summary: Subsea-rated electric motor used on an ROV subsystem (e.g., pumps/actuators), designed for reliable operation in harsh environments.
notes: Before replacement, confirm supply voltage, controller outputs and insulation resistance. Check for water ingress and bearing noise.
